## Description {#details}

This header defines various interfaces for pass management in LLVM.

There is no &quot;pass&quot; interface in LLVM per se. Instead, an instance of any class which supports a method to &#39;run&#39; it over a unit of IR can be used as a pass. A pass manager is generally a tool to collect a sequence of passes which run over a particular IR construct, and run each of them in sequence over each such construct in the containing IR construct. As there is no containing IR construct for a Module, a manager for passes over modules forms the base case which runs its managed passes in sequence over the single module provided.

The core IR library provides managers for running passes over modules and functions.


<ul>
<li>FunctionPassManager can run over a Module, runs each pass over a Function.</li>
<li>ModulePassManager must be directly run, runs each pass over the Module.</li>
</ul>


Note that the implementations of the pass managers use concept-based polymorphism as outlined in the &quot;Value Semantics and Concept-based
Polymorphism&quot; talk (or its abbreviated sibling &quot;Inheritance Is The Base
Class of Evil&quot;) by Sean Parent:
<ul>
<li><a href="https://sean-parent.stlab.cc/papers-and-presentations">https://sean-parent.stlab.cc/papers-and-presentations</a></li>
<li><a href="http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_BpMYeUFXv8">http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=&#95;BpMYeUFXv8</a></li>
<li><a href="https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/shows/goingnative-2013/inheritance-base-class-of-evil">https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/shows/goingnative-2013/inheritance-base-class-of-evil</a></li>
</ul>

<Link id="l00088" /><CodeLine lineNumber="88"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00093" /><CodeLine lineNumber="93"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Returns an opaque, unique ID for this analysis type.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00094" /><CodeLine lineNumber="94"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00095" /><CodeLine lineNumber="95"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// This ID is a pointer type that is guaranteed to be 8-byte aligned and thus</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00096" /><CodeLine lineNumber="96"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// suitable for use in sets, maps, and other data structures that use the low</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00097" /><CodeLine lineNumber="97"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// bits of pointers.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00098" /><CodeLine lineNumber="98"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00099" /><CodeLine lineNumber="99"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// Note that this requires the derived type provide a static \\c AnalysisKey</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00100" /><CodeLine lineNumber="100"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// member called \\c Key.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00101" /><CodeLine lineNumber="101"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00102" /><CodeLine lineNumber="102"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// FIXME: The only reason the mixin type itself can&#39;t declare the Key value</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00103" /><CodeLine lineNumber="103"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// is that some compilers cannot correctly unique a templated static variable</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00104" /><CodeLine lineNumber="104"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// so it has the same addresses in each instantiation. The only currently</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00105" /><CodeLine lineNumber="105"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// known platform with this limitation is Windows DLL builds, specifically</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00106" /><CodeLine lineNumber="106"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// building each part of LLVM as a DLL. If we ever remove that build</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00107" /><CodeLine lineNumber="107"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// configuration, this mixin can provide the static key as well.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00146" /><CodeLine lineNumber="146"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Manages a sequence of passes over a particular unit of IR.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00147" /><CodeLine lineNumber="147"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00148" /><CodeLine lineNumber="148"><Highlight kind="comment">/// A pass manager contains a sequence of passes to run over a particular unit</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00149" /><CodeLine lineNumber="149"><Highlight kind="comment">/// of IR (e.g. Functions, Modules). It is itself a valid pass over that unit of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00150" /><CodeLine lineNumber="150"><Highlight kind="comment">/// IR, and when run over some given IR will run each of its contained passes in</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00151" /><CodeLine lineNumber="151"><Highlight kind="comment">/// sequence. Pass managers are the primary and most basic building block of a</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00152" /><CodeLine lineNumber="152"><Highlight kind="comment">/// pass pipeline.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00153" /><CodeLine lineNumber="153"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00154" /><CodeLine lineNumber="154"><Highlight kind="comment">/// When you run a pass manager, you provide an \\c AnalysisManager&lt;IRUnitT&gt;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00155" /><CodeLine lineNumber="155"><Highlight kind="comment">/// argument. The pass manager will propagate that analysis manager to each</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00156" /><CodeLine lineNumber="156"><Highlight kind="comment">/// pass it runs, and will call the analysis manager&#39;s invalidation routine with</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00157" /><CodeLine lineNumber="157"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the PreservedAnalyses of each pass it runs.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00158" /><CodeLine lineNumber="158"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">template</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> &lt;</Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">typename</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> IRUnitT,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00159" /><CodeLine lineNumber="159"><Highlight kind="normal">          </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">typename</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> AnalysisManagerT = AnalysisManager&lt;IRUnitT&gt;,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00160" /><CodeLine lineNumber="160"><Highlight kind="normal">          </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">typename</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">... ExtraArgTs&gt;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00161" /><CodeLine lineNumber="161" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/passmanager"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/passmanager/#a8feea6425d71b06eb9eea6dfb60dcf4e">PassManager</a> : </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">public</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> <a href="/docs/api/structs/llvm/passinfomixin">PassInfoMixin</a>&lt;</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00283" /><CodeLine lineNumber="283"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// API to communicate dependencies between analyses during invalidation.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00284" /><CodeLine lineNumber="284"><Highlight kind="comment">  ///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00285" /><CodeLine lineNumber="285"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// When an analysis result embeds handles to other analysis results, it</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00286" /><CodeLine lineNumber="286"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// needs to be invalidated both when its own information isn&#39;t preserved and</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00287" /><CodeLine lineNumber="287"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// when any of its embedded analysis results end up invalidated. We pass an</Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00290" /><CodeLine lineNumber="290"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// This lets us avoid building an explicit representation of the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00291" /><CodeLine lineNumber="291"><Highlight kind="comment">  /// dependencies between analysis results.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00662" /><CodeLine lineNumber="662"><Highlight kind="comment">/// An analysis over an &quot;inner&quot; IR unit that provides access to an</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00663" /><CodeLine lineNumber="663"><Highlight kind="comment">/// analysis manager over a &quot;outer&quot; IR unit.  The inner unit must be contained</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00664" /><CodeLine lineNumber="664"><Highlight kind="comment">/// in the outer unit.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00665" /><CodeLine lineNumber="665"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00666" /><CodeLine lineNumber="666"><Highlight kind="comment">/// For example OuterAnalysisManagerProxy&lt;ModuleAnalysisManager, Function&gt; is an</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00667" /><CodeLine lineNumber="667"><Highlight kind="comment">/// analysis over Functions (the &quot;inner&quot; unit) which provides access to a Module</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00668" /><CodeLine lineNumber="668"><Highlight kind="comment">/// analysis manager.  The ModuleAnalysisManager is the &quot;outer&quot; manager being</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00669" /><CodeLine lineNumber="669"><Highlight kind="comment">/// proxied, and Modules are the &quot;outer&quot; IR unit.  The inner/outer relationship</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00670" /><CodeLine lineNumber="670"><Highlight kind="comment">/// is valid because each Function is contained in one Module.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00671" /><CodeLine lineNumber="671"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00672" /><CodeLine lineNumber="672"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This proxy only exposes the const interface of the outer analysis manager,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00673" /><CodeLine lineNumber="673"><Highlight kind="comment">/// to indicate that you cannot cause an outer analysis to run from within an</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00674" /><CodeLine lineNumber="674"><Highlight kind="comment">/// inner pass.  Instead, you must rely on the \\c getCachedResult API.  This is</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00675" /><CodeLine lineNumber="675"><Highlight kind="comment">/// due to keeping potential future concurrency in mind. To give an example,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00676" /><CodeLine lineNumber="676"><Highlight kind="comment">/// running a module analysis before any function passes may give a different</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00677" /><CodeLine lineNumber="677"><Highlight kind="comment">/// result than running it in a function pass. Both may be valid, but it would</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00678" /><CodeLine lineNumber="678"><Highlight kind="comment">/// produce non-deterministic results. GlobalsAA is a good analysis example,</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00679" /><CodeLine lineNumber="679"><Highlight kind="comment">/// because the cached information has the mod/ref info for all memory for each</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00680" /><CodeLine lineNumber="680"><Highlight kind="comment">/// function at the time the analysis was computed. The information is still</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00681" /><CodeLine lineNumber="681"><Highlight kind="comment">/// valid after a function transformation, but it may be &#42;different&#42; if</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00682" /><CodeLine lineNumber="682"><Highlight kind="comment">/// recomputed after that transform. GlobalsAA is never invalidated.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00683" /><CodeLine lineNumber="683"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="comment"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00684" /><CodeLine lineNumber="684"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00685" /><CodeLine lineNumber="685"><Highlight kind="comment">/// This proxy doesn&#39;t manage invalidation in any way -- that is handled by the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00686" /><CodeLine lineNumber="686"><Highlight kind="comment">/// recursive return path of each layer of the pass manager.  A consequence of</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00687" /><CodeLine lineNumber="687"><Highlight kind="comment">/// this is the outer analyses may be stale.  We invalidate the outer analyses</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00688" /><CodeLine lineNumber="688"><Highlight kind="comment">/// only when we&#39;re done running passes over the inner IR units.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00689" /><CodeLine lineNumber="689"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">template</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> &lt;</Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">typename</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> AnalysisManagerT, </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">typename</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"> IRUnitT, </Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">typename</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal">... ExtraArgTs&gt;</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00690" /><CodeLine lineNumber="690" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/outeranalysismanagerproxy"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/outeranalysismanagerproxy/#ac45b2069285adb1d482b5bd80b2b281c">OuterAnalysisManagerProxy</a></Highlight></CodeLine>

<Link id="l00804" /><CodeLine lineNumber="804"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Trivial adaptor that maps from a module to its functions.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00805" /><CodeLine lineNumber="805"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00806" /><CodeLine lineNumber="806"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Designed to allow composition of a FunctionPass(Manager) and</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00807" /><CodeLine lineNumber="807"><Highlight kind="comment">/// a ModulePassManager, by running the FunctionPass(Manager) over every</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00808" /><CodeLine lineNumber="808"><Highlight kind="comment">/// function in the module.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00809" /><CodeLine lineNumber="809"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00810" /><CodeLine lineNumber="810"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Function passes run within this adaptor can rely on having exclusive access</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00811" /><CodeLine lineNumber="811"><Highlight kind="comment">/// to the function they are run over. They should not read or modify any other</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00812" /><CodeLine lineNumber="812"><Highlight kind="comment">/// functions! Other threads or systems may be manipulating other functions in</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00813" /><CodeLine lineNumber="813"><Highlight kind="comment">/// the module, and so their state should never be relied on.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00814" /><CodeLine lineNumber="814"><Highlight kind="comment">/// FIXME: Make the above true for all of LLVM&#39;s actual passes, some still</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00815" /><CodeLine lineNumber="815"><Highlight kind="comment">/// violate this principle.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00816" /><CodeLine lineNumber="816"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00817" /><CodeLine lineNumber="817"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Function passes can also read the module containing the function, but they</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00818" /><CodeLine lineNumber="818"><Highlight kind="comment">/// should not modify that module outside of the use lists of various globals.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00819" /><CodeLine lineNumber="819"><Highlight kind="comment">/// For example, a function pass is not permitted to add functions to the</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00820" /><CodeLine lineNumber="820"><Highlight kind="comment">/// module.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00821" /><CodeLine lineNumber="821"><Highlight kind="comment">/// FIXME: Make the above true for all of LLVM&#39;s actual passes, some still</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00822" /><CodeLine lineNumber="822"><Highlight kind="comment">/// violate this principle.</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00823" /><CodeLine lineNumber="823"><Highlight kind="comment">///</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00824" /><CodeLine lineNumber="824"><Highlight kind="comment">/// Note that although function passes can access module analyses, module</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00825" /><CodeLine lineNumber="825"><Highlight kind="comment">/// analyses are not invalidated while the function passes are running, so they</Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00826" /><CodeLine lineNumber="826"><Highlight kind="comment">/// may be stale.  Function analyses will not be stale.</Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight></CodeLine>
<Link id="l00827" /><CodeLine lineNumber="827" lineLink="/docs/api/classes/llvm/moduletofunctionpassadaptor"><Highlight kind="normal"></Highlight><Highlight kind="keyword">class </Highlight><Highlight kind="normal"><a href="/docs/api/classes/llvm/moduletofunctionpassadaptor/#a3cd044b84398a56c814a9269401fdae4">ModuleToFunctionPassAdaptor</a></Highlight></CodeLine>
